<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-02-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="172" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d172">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Taylor</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 18.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-02-25"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 25, 1863.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your despatch of January 27 (No. 28) has
                            been received. I thank you most sincerely for the care you have so
                            judiciously bestowed upon the national cause, in translating for the
                            department the article in the Vedomosti, upon the President’s
                            proclamation. It is a paper of marked ability, candor, and foresight. I
                            shall cause it to be published here.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Bayard Taylor</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>